<tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter> <anchor>348</anchor> <addr>axt-000Y</addr> <sourcePath>/Users/ayberkt/Code/mathematical-forest/trees/axt-000Y.tree</sourcePath> <route>axt-000Y.xml</route> <date>September 15, 2023</date> <authors><author>Ayberk Tosun</author> </authors> <title>Filter base</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  A <em>filter base</em> on a nonempty set <tex>X</tex> is a family <tex>\{  B_i  \} _{i  \in  I}</tex>  of subsets of <tex>\mathcal{P} (X)</tex> satisfying the following properties:
  <ol>    <li><tex>I  \neq   \emptyset</tex> and <tex>B_i  \neq   \emptyset</tex> for each <tex>i  \in  I</tex></li>    <li>      For any two <tex>i, j  \in  I</tex>, there exists some <tex>k  \in  I</tex> such that
      <tex>B_k  \subseteq  B_i  \cap  B_j</tex>.
    </li>  </ol></p><p>  Adapted from the definition in page 21 of
  <link href="bridges-topological-and-uniform-2022.xml" type="local" title="Lectures on Topological and Uniform Spaces">Bridges' lecture notes</link>.
</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related/> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Theorem"><frontmatter> <anchor>350</anchor> <addr>axt-000X</addr> <sourcePath>/Users/ayberkt/Code/mathematical-forest/trees/axt-000X.tree</sourcePath> <route>axt-000X.xml</route> <date>September 15, 2023</date>  <title>Hausdorff property and filter bases</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  A space <tex>X</tex> is <link href="axt-000Q.xml" type="local" title="Hausdorff space (point-set)">Hausdorff</link> iff every <link href="axt-000Y.xml" type="local" title="Filter base">filter base</link> has at
  most one limit.
